why do we do ng build ?
high-level TypeScript into optimized JavaScript.

step - 1. ng build (The command looks into your package.json file under the "scripts" section)
step 2 - compiling (Browsers cannot read TypeScript. The build process runs the compiler to convert all your .ts files into .js)
step 3- bundling (uring development, you might have hundreds of small files. The builder follows the "imports" in your code to create a few large files (bundles).)
step 4 - Minification(To save bandwidth, the builder strips out:comments, whitespace,long var name to short,dead code which is not used)
step 5 - Hashing for Caching (build files often look like main.7a2b3c.js. This random string is a hash. If you change your code and rebuild, the hash changes. This tells the user's browser, "Hey, I have a new version, don't use the old cached one!")

guards - Guards are used to protect routes. If a user isn't logged in, you don't want them accessing the /admin dashboard.
       
 main types of guards in Angular:

CanActivate: Checks if a user can visit a route.

     canActivate(): boolean {
  if (this.authService.isLoggedIn()) {
    return true; // Let them in
  } else {
    this.router.navigate(['/login']);
    return false; // Block access
  }
}
CanActivateChild: Checks if a user can visit nested child routes.

CanDeactivate: Useful for asking, "Are you sure you want to leave?" (e.g., if there are unsaved changes in a form).

CanMatch: Determines if a route should even be considered for a path.

implement in app.routes.ts
// app.routes.ts
export const routes: Routes = [
  { 
    path: 'dashboard', 
    component: UserDashboardComponent, 
    canActivate: [authGuard] // Only logged-in users
  },
  { 
    path: 'admin/reports', 
    component: AdminReportsComponent, 
    canActivate: [authGuard, adminGuard] // Must be logged in AND an admin
  }
];


