package.json and package.lock.json ?
---> if a teammate clones your project and runs npm install, this section ensures they get the exact same versions of Angular, 
     RxJS, and TypeScript that you are using.

package.json -- created by using npm init
                 npm init -y to skip the questions
                 ng new stylehub-frontend. The Angular CLI automatically generated a package.json for 
                 you with all the necessary Angular dependencies already listed.

                 Version Ranges: It uses symbols like ^ or ~. For example, "@angular/core": "^17.3.0" means "I want version 17.3.0,
                 or any minor update like 17.4.0."

                 1. The Caret (^) — "The Balanced Update"
                    It allows updates to the Minor and Patch versions, but not the Major version.
                    Example: ^17.3.12
                    ✅ Can update to: 17.4.0 or 17.9.9
                    ❌ Will NOT update to: 18.0.0

                2. The Tilde (~) — "The Safe Bet"
                    It only allows updates to the Patch version. It locks the Major and Minor numbers.
                    Example: ~17.3.12
                    ✅ Can update to: 17.3.13 or 17.3.99
                    ❌ Will NOT update to: 17.4.0

package-lock.json -- (detailed version ) When you run npm install for the first time in a project that only has a package.json, 
                     npm looks at your list, goes to the internet to download them, and then writes the package-lock.json 
                     to record exactly what it found.
                     npm install lodash, npm does two things:
                     Adds "lodash" to your package.json. 
                     Updates package-lock.json with the exact version

                     Updates: When you run npm update, npm tries to find newer versions allowed by your
                      package.json ranges and updates the lockfile to reflect the new "locked" versions.